{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn1.23:1.1": "The “tangle” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>jaṭā</i>) is the tangled hair or dreadlocks of the Brahmanical <i lang='pi' translate='no'>jaṭila</i> ascetics, as is made clear in <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn7.6/en/sujato'>SN 7.6</a> where a dreadlocked brahmin opens with the same verse. The claim is that <i lang='pi' translate='no'>jaṭila</i> ascetics are as tangled in their minds by craving as they are in their hair. ",
    "sn1.23:2.1": "In a bold literary conceit, the vast compendium of the Visuddhimagga positions itself as an explanation of this single verse. ",
    "sn1.23:2.2": "Here <i lang='pi' translate='no'>citta</i> (“mind”) stands for <i lang='pi' translate='no'>samādhi</i> or <i lang='pi' translate='no'>jhāna</i>, which is normally the case in the Suttas on the path (eg. <i lang='pi' translate='no'>cittasampadā</i> = <i lang='pi' translate='no'>samādhisampadā</i>, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>cittabhāvanā</i> = <i lang='pi' translate='no'>samādhibhāvanā</i>, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>adhicitta</i> = <i lang='pi' translate='no'>samādhi</i>, etc.) ",
    "sn1.23:3.1": "The previous verse dealt with the one who is practicing; this verse with the perfected one; and the final verse with final extinguishment. "
  },
